  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions that address money laundering. These form the framework for national laws and international cooperation in combating money laundering. Here are some of the key ones:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first major international efforts to combat money laundering. It criminalized the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):** This convention expanded the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include the laundering of proceeds from a wide range of serious crimes.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention):** This convention addresses the laundering of proceeds derived from corruption.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty or convention, the FATF Recommendations are the global standard for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Over 200 countries and jurisdictions have committed to implementing these recommendations. They cover a wide range of measures, including:\n\n    *   Criminalizing money laundering and terrorist financing.\n    *   Implementing customer due diligence and record-keeping requirements for financial institutions.\n    *   Establishing financial intelligence units to receive and analyze suspicious transaction reports.\n    *   Promoting international cooperation in investigations and prosecutions.\n    *   Applying targeted financial sanctions.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) (Strasbourg Convention) and Revised Convention (2005):** These conventions aim to facilitate international cooperation in the tracing, freezing, seizure, and confiscation of proceeds of crime, including money laundering.\n\n**Key takeaways:**\n\n*   These international agreements create obligations for signatory states to criminalize money laundering, implement preventive measures, and cooperate internationally in investigations and prosecutions.\n*   The FATF Recommendations are particularly important as they set the global standard for anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist financing measures.\n*   The success of these laws depends on effective implementation and enforcement at the national level, as well as ongoing international cooperation.",
